threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB shared object, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, BuildID[sha1]=c293f00cd2ca44c0ecf41cc0194f14ad6cc67003, not stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This is a user-land rootkit that hooks standard library functions to hide its presence on the system. It uses `dlsym` to intercept calls like `readdir`, `fopen`, and various `stat` functions. The hooked `readdir` filters directory listings of `/proc` to hide malicious processes. The hooked `fopen` and `open` functions prevent access to hidden files and also call `hide_tcp_ports` to filter the content of network-related procfs files (e.g., `/proc/net/tcp`), effectively concealing malicious network connections. The malware uses a simple XOR routine to deobfuscate configuration strings.
